{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507336"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2623"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2623"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.71,0.04,0.02,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82730"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"286"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43987"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82730"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns of having some dust in her eyes after cleaning out her garage yesterday. She describes dryness, pain, and itchiness affecting both of her eyes currently, but denies any problems with her vision. Over the last year, she has been to her General Practitioner on multiple occasions with a similar complaint and has been given prescriptions for antibiotic eye drops, which have helped her symptoms. She has no relevant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital parameters within normal limits. Examination of her eyes reveals conjunctival injection, with no foreign bodies identified in either eye. Dye staining testing reveals keratoconjunctivitis sicca in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the next step to identify the likely diagnosis in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tonometry","Schirmer\u0027s test","Visual acuity testing","Direct and consensual pupillary reflex","Bacterial eye swab"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stem initially describes a presentation that could be explained by foreign bodies in her eyes, such as dust. But further history and the chronicity of her symptoms as well as the lack of foreign bodies identified suggest another cause. She is describing dry eyes, causing irritation and pain that is improved with the use of eyedrops. It is likely that the antibiotic eye drops are helping her symptoms due to the hydration they provide rather than the antibacterial properties. She also gives no other suggestion of an eye infection, hence a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial eye swab\u003C/strong\u003E would not be indicated at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeratoconjunctivitis sicca is chronic desiccation of the conjunctiva and cornea due to inadequate tears protecting them. It occurs bilaterally and is a characteristic ophthalmologic lesion of Sjogren syndrome. The \u003Cstrong\u003ESchirmer test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assist the diagnosis of Sjogren syndrome as it confirms ocular dryness. It is performed by placing a piece of filter paper on the inside of the lower eyelid, waiting and seeing how much moisture accumulates on the paper. This test can help to confirm that the patient is in fact suffering from dry eyes, but does not form the diagnosis of Sjogren syndrome, which requires further investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonometry \u003C/strong\u003Eis the testing of the pressure inside the eyes. It is commonly used to identify or test for glaucoma. There is no indication from this stem that glaucoma is likely, the patient describes no visual problems and hence would not be the most appropriate next investigation. Similarly, as the patient does not describe any issues with her \u003Cstrong\u003Evisual acuity,\u003C/strong\u003E although this testing would likely be done it would not help to point towards the diagnosis of Sjogren syndrome. Additionally, although \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect and consensual pupillary reaction\u003C/strong\u003E testing formulates a complete eye examination there is no suggestion from the stem or symptoms that there may be problems with her optic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schirmer\u0027s test is used to demonstrate a person is suffering from dry eyes.","Sjogren syndrome is an autoimmune condition causing sicca (dry eyes and mouth).","Keratoconjunctivitis sicca is a common manifestation of Sjogren syndrome, characterised by chronic dry eyes."],"references":["Brott NR, Zeppieri M, Ronquillo Y. Schirmer Test. [Updated 2024 Feb 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559159/","Stevens S. Schirmer\u0027s test. Community Eye Health. 2011;24(76):45. Available at: https://www.cehjournal.org/article/schirmers-test/","Carsons SE, Patel BC. Sjogren Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431049/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2623"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T21:42:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T21:45:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2623"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82730"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"he